    {
      "question": "If $\\sin \\theta + \\cos \\theta = \\sqrt{2} \\cos \\theta$, then prove that $\\cos \\theta - \\sin \\theta = \\sqrt{2} \\sin \\theta$.",
      "answer": "Proof",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Square both sides of the given equation.",
          "Use $\\sin^2 \\theta + \\cos^2 \\theta = 1$.",
          "Solve for $\\cos \\theta$ in terms of $\\sin \\theta$.",
          "Substitute this into the required expression.",
          "Verify equality."
        ],
        "derivation": "(\\sin \\theta + \\cos \\theta)^2 = 2\\cos^2 \\theta \\implies 1 + 2\\sin \\theta \\cos \\theta = 2\\cos^2 \\theta \\implies 2\\sin \\theta \\cos \\theta = 2\\cos^2 \\theta - 1. \\text{ Now, } (\\cos \\theta - \\sin \\theta)^2 = \\cos^2 \\theta + \\sin^2 \\theta - 2\\sin \\theta \\cos \\theta = 1 - (2\\cos^2 \\theta - 1) = 2 - 2\\cos^2 \\theta = 2\\sin^2 \\theta. \\therefore \\cos \\theta - \\sin \\theta = \\sqrt{2} \\sin \\theta."
      },
