      "question": "If $\\sec \\theta + \\tan \\theta = p$, prove that $\\sin \\theta = \\frac{p^2 - 1}{p^2 + 1}$.",
      "answer": "Proof",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Use the identity $\\sec^2 \\theta - \\tan^2 \\theta = 1$.",
          "Factorize to get $(\\sec \\theta - \\tan \\theta)(\\sec \\theta + \\tan \\theta) = 1$.",
          "Express $\\sec \\theta - \\tan \\theta = 1/p$.",
          "Solve for $\\sec \\theta$ and $\\tan \\theta$ in terms of $p$.",
          "Calculate $\\sin \\theta = \\tan \\theta / \\sec \\theta$."
        ],
        "derivation": "\\sec \\theta + \\tan \\theta = p, \\sec \\theta - \\tan \\theta = 1/p. \\implies 2\\sec \\theta = p + 1/p = (p^2+1)/p, 2\\tan \\theta = p - 1/p = (p^2-1)/p. \\sin \\theta = \\frac{\\tan \\theta}{\\sec \\theta} = \\frac{(p^2-1)/2p}{(p^2+1)/2p} = \\frac{p^2-1}{p^2+1}."
      },
