      "question": "If $x = a \\sec \\theta + b \\tan \\theta$ and $y = a \\tan \\theta + b \\sec \\theta$, prove that $x^2 - y^2 = a^2 - b^2$.",
      "answer": "Proof",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Square the expressions for $x$ and $y$.",
          "Subtract $y^2$ from $x^2$.",
          "Group terms with $a^2$ and $b^2$.",
          "Use $\\sec^2 \\theta - \\tan^2 \\theta = 1$.",
          "Simplify the resulting expression."
        ],
        "derivation": "x^2 = a^2 \\sec^2 \\theta + b^2 \\tan^2 \\theta + 2ab \\sec \\theta \\tan \\theta. y^2 = a^2 \\tan^2 \\theta + b^2 \\sec^2 \\theta + 2ab \\sec \\theta \\tan \\theta. x^2 - y^2 = a^2(\\sec^2 \\theta - \\tan^2 \\theta) - b^2(\\sec^2 \\theta - \\tan^2 \\theta) = a^2(1) - b^2(1) = a^2 - b^2."
