      "question": "Prove that $\\sqrt{\\frac{1 + \\sin \\theta}{1 - \\sin \\theta}} = \\sec \\theta + \\tan \\theta$.",
      "answer": "Proof",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Rationalize the denominator inside the square root.",
          "Use $(1+\\sin \\theta)(1+\\sin \\theta) = (1+\\sin \\theta)^2$.",
          "Use $(1-\\sin \\theta)(1+\\sin \\theta) = 1-\\sin^2 \\theta = \\cos^2 \\theta$.",
          "Remove the square root.",
          "Split the fraction."
        ],
        "derivation": "\\sqrt{\\frac{(1+\\sin \\theta)^2}{(1-\\sin \\theta)(1+\\sin \\theta)}} = \\sqrt{\\frac{(1+\\sin \\theta)^2}{\\cos^2 \\theta}} = \\frac{1+\\sin \\theta}{\\cos \\theta} = \\frac{1}{\\cos \\theta} + \\frac{\\sin \\theta}{\\cos \\theta} = \\sec \\theta + \\tan \\theta."
