      "question": "If $\\cos \\theta + \\sin \\theta = \\sqrt{2} \\sin \\theta$, show that $\\cos \\theta - \\sin \\theta = \\sqrt{2} \\cos \\theta$. (Note: check coefficients carefully)",
      "answer": "Proof",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Start with $\\cos \\theta = (\\sqrt{2}-1)\\sin \\theta$.",
          "Multiply both sides by $(\\sqrt{2}+1)$.",
          "Use difference of squares on the right side.",
          "Simplify to get $\\sin \\theta = (\\sqrt{2}+1)\\cos \\theta$.",
          "Rearrange to verify the target equation."
        ],
